

Graphic at http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_u1GIE0NHH8g/Sh3SMKkllGI/AAAAAAAAACw/v_X-zB5nlIw/s1600-h/club+goods.jpg

It distinguishes rivalrous/non-rivalrous goods and excludable/non-excludable on two axes, giving 4 quadrants:

* Private goods are rivalrous and excludable, i.e. toys or cars

* [[Common Goods]] or [[Common Pool Resources]] are rivalrous and non-excludable, i.e. fish and water

* [[Club Goods]] are non-rivalrous but excludable, i.e. satellite TV

* [[Public Goods]] are non-rivalrous, and non-excludable, i.e. free to air TV

Commentary by David Ronfeldt at http://twotheories.blogspot.com/2009/05/timn-table-details-learning-that-tribes.html


